# Embedded C Standards

## Naming
- Functions and variables: `snake_case`
- Macros and constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Type definitions: `snake_case_t` (e.g. `msg_header_t`)
- Public API functions: prefixed with module name (e.g. `rpmsg_lite_init()`)
- Static functions: no prefix needed, keep descriptive

## Memory & Safety
- Prefer stack allocation over heap in ISR and time-critical paths
- Always check return values from system calls and allocations
- Use `static` for file-scoped functions and variables
- Prefer fixed-size types from `<stdint.h>` (`uint32_t`, `int8_t`, etc.)
- Avoid dynamic allocation in ISR context

## Structure
- One public header per module, internal headers prefixed with `_` or in a `private/` dir
- Keep functions short — if it exceeds ~60 lines, consider splitting
- Group related declarations: includes, defines, types, static vars, static functions, public API

## Error Handling
- Return error codes, do not silently ignore failures
- Use the platform's error/logging API (`LOG_ERR`, `ESP_LOGE`, `pr_err`, etc.)
- Log with meaningful context: what failed and relevant parameter values

## KalangoRTOS related
- Enforce on kernel side static allocation
- Public API goes to the kalango_api.h file and should be namespaced as Kalango_
- Platform specific code is only allowed in arch folder of the target platform including arch dependent files
- New kalango config symbols should receive a default value in kalango_config_internal.h
- Kalango kernel code should target low-latency hard-real-time as possible.
